      "source": [
        "%%markdown\n",
        "### Basic Decorator Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "A decorator is essentially a function that takes another function as input, adds some functionality, and returns a new function (often called a wrapper function). The basic structure involves:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.  An **outer function** (the decorator) that accepts a function as an argument.\n",
        "2.  An **inner function** (the wrapper) defined inside the outer function. This inner function is where the additional logic is placed, and it calls the original function.\n",
        "3.  The outer function **returns** the inner function."
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>"
            ],
            "text/markdown": "### Basic Decorator Structure\n\nA decorator is essentially a function that takes another function as input, adds some functionality, and returns a new function (often called a wrapper function). The basic structure involves:\n\n1.  An **outer function** (the decorator) that accepts a function as an argument.\n2.  An **inner function** (the wrapper) defined inside the outer function. This inner function is where the additional logic is placed, and it calls the original function.\n3.  The outer function **returns** the inner function.\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
