        "**Reasoning**:\n",
        "Add a markdown cell explaining the issue of losing function metadata and how `functools.wraps` solves it.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 177
        },
        "id": "a03d3b83",
        "outputId": "d68e0701-4dec-41a0-8f57-91c58433c052"
      },
      "source": [
        "%%markdown\n",
        "### Preserving Metadata with `functools.wraps`\n",
        "\n",
        "When you use a decorator, the original function is replaced by the wrapper function returned by the decorator. This process can lead to the loss of important metadata from the original function, such as its name (`__name__`), docstring (`__doc__`), module (`__module__`), and dictionary (`__dict__`). Debugging and introspection can become difficult because the decorated function appears to be the wrapper function.\n",
        "\n",
        "The `functools` module provides the `@functools.wraps(original_function)` decorator specifically to address this issue. When applied to the wrapper function inside your decorator, `@wraps` copies the relevant metadata from the original function (`original_function`) to the wrapper function. This makes the decorated function look and behave more like the original function, preserving its identity and documentation."
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>"
            ],
            "text/markdown": "### Preserving Metadata with `functools.wraps`\n\nWhen you use a decorator, the original function is replaced by the wrapper function returned by the decorator. This process can lead to the loss of important metadata from the original function, such as its name (`__name__`), docstring (`__doc__`), module (`__module__`), and dictionary (`__dict__`). Debugging and introspection can become difficult because the decorated function appears to be the wrapper function.\n\nThe `functools` module provides the `@functools.wraps(original_function)` decorator specifically to address this issue. When applied to the wrapper function inside your decorator, `@wraps` copies the relevant metadata from the original function (`original_function`) to the wrapper function. This makes the decorated function look and behave more like the original function, preserving its identity and documentation.\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
