        "### Explaining the Timing Decorator Example\n",
        "\n",
        "This example demonstrates how the `timing_decorator` adds execution time measurement to the `complex_operation` function without altering the `complex_operation`'s code itself.\n",
        "\n",
        "- We import `time` for measuring time and `functools` for `@functools.wraps`.\n",
        "- The `timing_decorator` is defined. It takes a function `func` as input.\n",
        "- Inside the decorator, `wrapper_timer` is defined. This is the function that will actually be called when `complex_operation` is executed.\n",
        "    - `@functools.wraps(func)` is applied to `wrapper_timer`. This is crucial because it copies the name (`complex_operation`) and docstring (`Simulates a complex operation...`) from the original `complex_operation` function to the `wrapper_timer`. This makes debugging and introspection easier, as shown in the previous section.\n",
